There once was a Western Whiptail Lizard making its home around my house. On early Monday mornings, trash days, I moved the blue bin very carefully to the curb because the lizard spent the nights under it. Sometimes it made its way into my garage. Yesterday it jumped out of an empty flower pot as I walked by. Each time I saw it I grabbed the camera hoping it would allow me to take a picture. No such luck. It was a very, very shy lizard. I was working away on the computer and heard unusual amounts of rustling in the dry leaves under the shrubs in front of my window. I jumped up and looked -- into the eyes of a Greater Roadrunner, holding the Western Whiptail Lizard in its beak. I was thinking, oh no, the poor Lizzie, but admittedly, also feeling a little excited, and happy for the Roadrunner to have found a meal. I'm sure you all know what I'm talking about, these mixed feelings and the heartbreak when nature isn't all cute kitten pix. The Roadrunner took its prey to the street and smashed it onto the asphalt, over and over again. This gave me a moment to find the camera and sneak outside and take a few hectic pictures...   (Western Whiptail observation: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/14271438)
Eating a rat it caught in my chicken pen

As I was taking a picture of this female Common Merganser (Gänsesäger) in the channel at the entry of Nymphenburg Palace, she suddenly raced away with her bill and eyes under water. I first thought she was chasing Black-headed Gulls, but she surfaced with a Chub that was so large and heavy that she lost her grip on it. She must have stunned the fish, because she pulled it out again after searching for it under water. This time, she didn’t only struggle with the weight of the fish, she was also surrounded by excited Gulls who wanted to get a bite. The Merganser tried in vein to get airborne with the heavy load, and eventually had to drop her prey… She seemed pumped up and excited after this catch and shook her feathers and flapped her wings for a bit. And then she continued her search.
For the Chub: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/34861851

column43:
This roadrunner was at a bird feeder at Sandia Crest (~10,678 feet elevation!) and was first observed lying flat in the seed tray of the feeder. After it was disturbed by me and left, a few Mountain Chickadees arrived at the feeder. When I returned to the spot sometime later, the roadrunner was back in the feeder tray and then was observed on the ground under the feeder swallowing a bird -- perhaps a chickadee it had caught. Unfortunately I missed the actual capture of the prey bird. 

See: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/112342231

I came across the pair apparently shortly after the snake had bitten the toad, around 14:30. In the video the adder can be seen giving the toad a second bite.
The snake started swallowing the toad at 14:38, the toad still struggling strongly. The toad stopped moving at around 14:41.
Initially I started filming on my phone as the snake was blocking the path to my camera and I didn't want to disturb it. An hour in (15:30), it was apparent that the snake was untroubled by the various humans and cats watching it, and I swapped to the camera.
By 16:50 the snake had swallowed the toad up to its hips. At 17:16 it partially regurgitated the prey and started swallowing again.
At 17:36 it again regurgitated a large portion of the toad - its front legs and feet were visible.
At 17:56 only the back legs were still protruding.
The toad was completely swallowed at 18:09, 3.5 hours in all.
The video (3mins 30 sec) is edited and speeded up 2x.

Video
https://youtu.be/hejRBqj_PS0

column43:
Our San Jose pest controller Sneakers the Cat with a "bushy-tailed tree rat".  Eastern Gray Squirrels and Fox Squirrels have been introduced to many park areas in many large cities, and their populations have spread to the rural areas around those cities. These squirrels are tolerant of human activity, and even thrive in crowded urban and suburban environments. They exploit human habitations for sources of food and nesting sites, and are considered as "pests" in many areas, including my old San Jose backyard. 
Sneakers did NOT like eating the rats or mice that he caught, but this young Eastern Gray Squirrel was an exception, especially after I skinned and cooked it on the backyard Bar-B-Que grill for him, our dog Pepper, and myself. It was about time that my cat "fed" me a bit .........

https://subsites.wur.nl/upload_mm/e/e/8/be98b401-0126-4123-b8e2-65f7c7865f15_extra-info-granen.pdf

The spikelets bear up to twelve florets, mostly with a single glume, with only the terminal floret having two. The glumes are up to three-quarters the length of the spikelet; their outer surface is finely ribbed with longitudinal veins. There is no awn, the lemma is oblong and has five nerves and the palea is a similar shape with two nerve and a few fine hairs. The three anthers are yellow.
https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lolium_rigidum

Description

L. rigidum is an annual species forming open tussocks. The dominant habit is erect, but the species is variable in habit, ranging from dense prostrate to more open erect types. Geniculate stems, fibrous root system, up to 1 m high. Reddish-purple colouration at base of stems extends upwards as the plant matures. Leaf blades dark green, hairless, flat, upper surface evenly ribbed, lower surface smooth and shiny, 5-25 cm long, 3-5 mm wide. Young leaves rolled in bud. Auricles small and narrow. Ligule, white, translucent, shorter than wide. Leaf sheath hairless, with fine longitudinal ribs as in leaf blades, reddish-purple at base. Inflorescence is a spike up to 30 cm in length; spikelets edge on to the rachis. Rachis is recessed opposite each spikelet, which more or less fits into the recess. Spikelets of 10-12 florets, laterally flattened, green, 10-25 mm long. Only the terminal spikelet has two more or less equal glumes. Otherwise only one glume subtending each spikelet, lanceloate, 10-15 mm long, two-thirds to three-quarters as long as the spikelet, outer surface fine-veined, ribbed like the upper surface of the leaf blade. No awn. Lemma lanceolate, about 5 mm long, five nerved, usually with no awn, but terminal awns occasionally found, probably as a result of hybridization. Palea similar to lemma in shape and size, two nerves with tiny hairs along them. Anthers three, yellow.

Description of two new species of Stigmaeopsis, Banks 1917 (Acari, Tetranychidae) inhabiting Miscanthus grasses (Poaceae)

Systematik
Erstmals systematisch beschrieben wurde die Bambusmilbe 1917 unter dem lateinischen Namen Stigmaeopsis celarius. 1950 wurde die Art neu beschrieben und der Gattung Schizotetranychus angegliedert. Dementsprechend wird man unter den Artnamen Schizotetranychus celarius die meiste Literatur finden. Vor kurzem allerdings wurde die Gattung Stigmaeopsis – aufgrund detaillierter molekularbiologischer und morphologischer Studien – wieder allein gestellt (Saito et al., 2004). Unterdessen konnten 7 Arten beschrieben werden, Stigmaeopsis celarius, Stigmaeopsis longus, Stigmaeopsis miscanthi, Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis, Stigmaeopsis tenuinidus, Stigmaeopsis sahara und Stigmaeopsis takahashii, von denen 6 auch tatsächlich an Bambus parasitieren. Nach einer vorläufigen Bestimmung durch Prof. Yutaka Saito (Hokkaido University, Japan) scheint es sich bei der in Deutschland verbreiteten Milbe um Stigmaeopsis longus oder Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis zu handeln (Prof. Saito, persönliche Mitteilung). Wahrscheinlich handelt es sich um Stigmaeopsis longus, da v.a. ältere Blätter befallen werden und Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis dafür bekannt ist, – zu mindest in China – junge Moso-Blätter im zeitigen Frühjahr zu befallen und zu schädigen.
https://bambus-deutschland.de/index.php/bambus-kultur/schaedlinge/die-gruppe-der-bambusmilben-stigmaeopsis/

the variation in nest size of the eight species corresponded well with the variation in dorsal seta sc1 length, suggesting that nest size variation among species may have a genetic basis. The time spent within a nest (nest duration) increased with nest size on the respective host plants. Nest arrangement patterns varied among species showing different sized nests: Large nest builders continuously extended their nests, while middle and small nest-building species built new separate nests, which resulted in different social interaction times among species, and is thought to be closely related to social development. Fecal deposition behaviors also varied among Stigmaeopsis species, suggesting diversity in anti-predatory adaptations.

Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis (Acari: Tetranychidae) has recently been found on bamboo species (Phyllostachys sp., P. viridiglaucescens, S. yashadake) in Alpes-maritimes, Hérault, Gard and Hérault departments. The first specimens had been collected in Gard in 2003 but were misidentified as S. celarius. Until recently, S. nanjingensis was only known to occur in China, but it has been found in Italy, Hungary and Portugal. The related species S. longus was first reported in the EPPO region in 2020 in the Netherlands (RS 2020/247), also introduced with bamboo plants.

So far, in Europe, two species of alien tetranychid 
mites have been recorded on bamboos, namely Stigmaeopsis celarius Banks in The Netherlands, Great 
Britain, Belgium and France, and Schizotetranychus 
bambusae Reck in France only (Vierbergen, 1997; 
Ostoja-Starzewski, 2000; Auger and Migeon, 2007). S. 
celarius is also widespread in the USA. 
Presently, the S. celarius complex consists of seven 
species: S. celarius, S. nanjingensis, S. longus (Saito), S. 
miscanthi (Saito), (the last two previously known as celarius in Japan), S. tenuinidis (Zhang et Zhang), S. saharai Saito et Mori and S. takahashi Saito et Mori, (Saito et al., 2004). Of these, only S. miscanthi inhabits plants other than bamboo.

Presently S. nanjingensis is widespread in the Veneto Region (North-Eastern Italy) on ornamental bamboos (Phyllostachys mitis, P. nigra and, to a less extent, Pseudosasa japonica). Infestations were observed in Padua, Treviso and Vicenza districts, both in new and old plantations of historical parks. Moreover it has been recorded also in the Liguria region (North-western Italy), at Ventimiglia (Imperia district), near the French border. The infested plants are easily recognizable by the whitish-yellow spots on the upper side of leaves.

Die 8 untersuchten Bambusmilbenarten der Gattung Stigmaeopsis unterscheiden sich unter anderem in der Art des Nestbaues und in der sozialen Organisation. Dabei treten zwei Extreme auf. Zum einem gibt es Arten, die – wie die bei uns eingescheppten Bambusmilben (Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis oder Stigmaeopsis longus) – große, aneinanderhängende Nester mit vielen Individuen bauen, welche beim Gegenangriff auf Räuber zusammenarbeiten können. Zum anderen gibt es Arten, die das Risiko eines Angriffs durch Räuber reduzieren, indem sie verstreut liegende kleine und feste Nester bauen, die nur mit größerem Aufwand aufgestöbert werden können und in welche die Räuber nur schlecht eindringen können. Die Individuen dieser Arten zeigen keinen Gegenangriff.



Daneben gibt es auch interessante Zwischen- bzw. Sonderformen des Nestbaus, auf die ich hier jedoch nicht näher eingehen möchte.



Interessant ist vielleicht noch, dass die Milben ihr Nest nicht mit ihren schlecht entwickelten Augen erkennen, sondern mithilfe bestimmter Borsten auf dem Rücken ertasten. Milbenarten mit größeren Borsten bauen auch größere Nester.



Insgesamt wurden 5 Arten der Kotablage beobachtet:
1. Ein einzelner Ablageplatz innerhalb des Nestes (Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis)
2. Ein einzelner Ablageplatz außerhalb des Nestes (Stigmaeopsis longus)
3. Zwei Ablageplätze außerhalb des Nestes
4. Mehrere Ablageplätze in unmittelbarer Nähe der Nestöffnungen
5. Weit entfernt von den Nestöffnungen wahllos verteilte Ablageplätze

column43:
Merlin had a lucky day and was eating a juicy meal (something with feathers) in Montreal, Canada. Photo credit: L.P.

Merlin (Falco columbarius) is a fast-flying falcon in the Falcons and Caracaras (Falconidae) family. It is "small falcon, compact and fast-flying. The Merlin is a common breeder across the northern forests of North America and Eurasia. It feeds mostly on small birds, capturing them in mid-air in rapid pursuit. The Merlin is generally found in wild places, but since about 1960 it has become a common urban bird in several towns on the northern prairies; there it nests and remains to winter, relying on a steady supply of House Sparrows as prey."

Audubon Guide to North American Birds: https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/merlin

Ebird with species description, range map and sound recordings: https://ebird.org/species/merlin
Merlin is a "small and fierce falcon. It is dark above and paler below, with streaking on the underparts; darkness of plumage varies geographically. It feeds mainly on birds captured in flight. It is found in a variety of habitats from grasslands, urban areas, open forests, and especially coastal areas with shorebirds. It flies powerfully on pointed wings with quick, continuous wingbeats."

column43:
Nature is metal, as they say.

There were tons of gulls and blackbirds at Kings Beach today. And there were tons of people watching and photographing the gulls. But nobody seemed to be paying much attention to the blackbirds which, I guess, is to be expected. But that was unfortunate for them because when blackbirds scatter and/or fly off in a flock, it's worth taking a closer look.

As I walked past a tree filled with blackbirds, their chatter increased and they quickly bolted. I looked up and saw one bigger bird amongst the crowd. Sure enough, a Peregrine Falcon swooped in for some takeout!

Within seconds, the Peregrine Falcon had caught, killed, and flew off with its lunch. Crazy fast and I'm willing to bet that I was the only person to even notice. Even in a developed area such as this, awesome nature interactions are taking place!

column72:
Some old pictures I found of when my chickens were playing keep away with a dead sparrow. I'm not sure if they found it dead or managed to kill it or how long they'd had it, but it was pretty beaten up since they had thrown it around and pecked holes in its chest.

They were all very keen to eat it so they were constantly stealing it from one another and running away with it. I took a few pictures and then chased them down to get it back since I didn't want them eating another bird especially since I didn't know how it died. They were very reluctant to give it up and devastated when they weren't allowed to eat it.

House sparrows were common in our yard when we had chickens since they loved the chicken scratch feed. They would feed very close to the chickens so I don't doubt that they would be able to grab one not paying attention. The sparrow also potentially hit the window and the chickens took advantage of it being stunned or killed.

Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/19QeK74z6v/

Another elegant Assassin 🙂

We recently came across other Assassin Bugs that looked somewhat similar to this one here (a light-coloured one): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/282814263, and here (a dark-coloured one): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/282812233

It looks as if this is possibly a Vadimon sp.: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/642553-Vadimon and similar to Vadimon cf. bergrothi: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/694994-Vadimon-bergrothi and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/694994-Vadimon-bergrothi/browse_photos.

As Andrew Schild pointed out, "This one looks like it may have a Tachinid egg attached to its body; it may not be long for this world... - the larva will likely start to feed on the Assassin. A number of Tachinids target Pentatomomorph Bugs (Pentatomomorpha)." 😕 That certainly doesn't sound too great, but we have seen other insects in similar situations where things could still change, such as this moth: https://www.facebook.com/groups/Butterfliesandbugs/permalink/9081588435271909/?app=fbl. 

On the lookout in the bush in Gulu, on the outskirts of East London, Eastern Cape, South Africa 🇿🇦

It looks as if they are those of a Common Mimic Acraea, Telchinia encedon ssp. encedon: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1482671-Telchinia-encedon-encedon and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1482671-Telchinia-encedon-encedon/browse_photos.

Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1Twm3vLAVG!

As mentioned in our other main mielie post, (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283369531) we're delving behind some mielie ears and sharing what we've found.

🌍 Aphids everywhere

These little ones were tucked between the bracts of some of the mielies. It seems they didn't get all the way through to the cob, unlike the African Bollworm Moth caterpillars we found earlier who must have tunneled all the way in via the corn silk head: https://www.facebook.com/groups/Butterfliesandbugs/permalink/7217403928357045/?app=fbl.

In the first two videos (see original Facebook post link) we see a brief glimpse of an aphid-farming ant zipping past. The quiet pasture has been discovered! In the second video and third videos the cattle are roaming...there is also a whitish larva (discussed further here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283499883), squirming right behind the aphid.

What type of aphids could these be? 🤔

Edit: After investigating further, we came to the conclusion none of the current locally-reported aphid species on INaturalist seem to fit, but the Corn Leaf Aphid, Rhopalosiphum maidis does: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/330189-Rhopalosiphum-maidis. "Rhopalosiphum maidis, common names corn leaf aphid and corn aphid, is an insect, and a pest of maize and other crops. It has a nearly worldwide distribution and is typically found in agricultural fields, grasslands, and forest-grassland zones." 

Searching a little further afield we found that the presence of this aphid has indeed been reported on by the South African Agricultural Research Council: https://www.arc.agric.za/arc-sgi/Pages/Crop%20Protection/Insect-pests-of-leaves-and-stems.aspx. Thanks for confirming the ID of these little ones Natalie Hernandez* - much appreciated! 

*Natalie has a B.S. and M.Sc. in Entomology from the University of Wisconsin - Madison (USA) and her graduate research focused on alate aphids.

There is an interesting discussion about the potential origin of all these insects in one of our other posts here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283414486

Unusual cattle and farmers in Gulu, on the outskirts of East London, Eastern Cape, South Africa 🇿🇦

Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/16NCxxufnF

⚠️🌍 **Multiple organisms**

Yaaaaaay! 😄

🌍 Finally, we've found two adult / imago Green Stink Bugs (Nezara viridula): https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/141725-Nezara-viridula, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/141725-Nezara-viridula/browse_photos. Thanks dhjacobs and colin25 for the ID confirmation 🙂

We had previously found many instars leading up to this: https://www.facebook.com/groups/Butterfliesandbugs/permalink/7186995038064601/?app=fbl.

The adults are completely leathery-green, with lovely "bug-eyes" and jointed antennae. The upper portions of the legs are green and the lower, brown.

The first 4 piccies are an adult on a mielie stalk, showing "Dali-moustache-like" antennae (the bug has clearly been munching on the side of the stalk, and the ant 🐜 looks happy 😃) 

The other 4 piccies are of another adult on a mielie leaf nearby.

According to the Wikipedia article about this bug, when ready to mate, the bug sounds a 100 Hz vibration that allows bi-directional communication to any Nezara standing on the same plant so they can find each other! Just for fun you can hear what 100Hz sounds like here👂: https://youtu.be/Cdi0jQtMqV8?si=S452_Uv-Zxr2Anb7. It's veeeeeeryyy still, so you have to have ears to hear or feet to feel. 🥰 Here's to hope! 🍾🥂 May they find one another soon! 💚💚

🌍 Side note: There also happens to be an ant 🐜 (third piccy and separately posted here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/312411583) that's enjoying the damage created by the Stink Bugs 🤭

All grown up in Gulu, on the outskirts of East London, Eastern Cape, South Africa 🇿🇦

column43:
Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/15jghWWMNa/

A rather peculiar little thing we found on a Lantana flower.

It's about 7mm long.

It looks as if this might possibly be a Lantana Leaf Beetle, Octotoma scabripennis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/310775-Octotoma-scabripennis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/310775-Octotoma-scabripennis/browse_photos. Thanks for the ID confirmation Cameron Ramsey and Tony Rebelo! 🙂

"Octotoma scabripennis, known as the lantana leafminer and lantana leaf beetle, is a species of beetle in the family Chrysomelidae, originally from Central America and introduced into Australia to kill the previously invasive Lantana camara plant."

Interestingly enough this beetle was apparently also introduced here in South Africa, as one of many measures attempting to control invasive Lantana before 1997, according to this article by David Simelane, from the Agricultural Research Council (ARC): "Lantana camara (Verbenaceae)": https://www.arc.agric.za/arc-ppri/Pages/Lantana-camara.aspx.

According to this Fact Sheet from the Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry
Biosecurity Queensland in Australia: "Lantana Biocontrol, Octotoma scabripennis" (October 2013): https://www.daf.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/66458/IPA-Lantana-Biocontrol-3.pdf

"•  Octotoma scabripennis occurs naturally from Mexico to Nicaragua.
 •  Cultures of Octotoma scabripennis originated from Mexico.
 •  The insect was first released in Australia in 1966.
 •  Adults feed on the upper surfaces of leaves, leaving small scarification marks.
 •  Eggs are laid on the edge of adult feeding scars.
 •  Larvae feed in middle leaf layers, causing dark blotches.
 •  Pupation occurs in the leaves.
 •  Development from egg to adult takes 34–45 days.
 •  Adults live for 6–9 months, but may enter a period of inactivity during winter when conditions are unfavourable."

Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1AmLUPBfYS/

Despite our recent rather mixed caterpillar rearing experience: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285291566, in which our larger caterpillars ended up being parasitised by wasps, we still managed to find a few smaller caterpillars on our lettuces: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285277062, and we've decided to give it another go...

Here they are...very small (about 1.5cm), but two of the three have already pupated. Oddly enough, one has wrapped itself in some lettuce and the other has apparently decided to wrap itself inside the toilet tissue we put underneath to make the "floor" less cold.

Suncana Bradley previously identified these smaller caterpillars as potentially being the larvae of one of the lovely Crambid Snout Moths (Crambidae family): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285265884, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/52002-Crambidae and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=52002&view=species.

Here's to hoping they were too small to be stung! 

Update: Thankfully the little caterpillars all blossomed and became beautiful Rusty Dot Pearl moths: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285342567. Thanks Suncana! You were right on the money! 💚🧡😄

Trying again in Gulu, on the outskirts of East London, Eastern Cape, South Africa 🇿🇦

Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1DXdgV29Fk/

This group does strange things to your heart! 😄🥰🐛💚🌱

This may sound a little loopy, but we're really excited to find a new batch of caterpillars on our radishes (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/288644081)! 😃 

Last time we also found two types on our lettuces: big ones with what look like wraparound sunglasses, and smaller ones without.

Sadly, but interestingly, we later discovered that the wraparound sunglass caterpillars had previously been stung by Braconid Wasps, so just as they were ready to pupate the wasp cocoons mushroomed out all over their bodies 😥😢😭...it was quite awful to see, but we ended up rearing the wasps to see what they look like: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285277062 and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285291566.

The smaller caterpillars thankfully ended up turning into some adorable Rusty Dot Pearl moths: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285334721 and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285342567.

Interestingly we now have the caterpillars in a transparent container - you can *see* 👀 the caterpillars weaving their cocoons!

We're rearing to go! 😄🥰

Update: Wonderful news: it would appear that after 13-19 days from starting to cocoon, these caterpillars became beautiful Scar Bank Gem or Silver U-Tail Moths, Ctenoplusia limbirena 😃: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285497257, https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285513280 and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285516396. Even more surprising was the discovery of an additional one we didn't even know about 😊: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285518534. Thanks for the ID confirmation Suncana Bradley 🙂

Really looking forward to seeing what will become of these in Gulu, on the outskirts of East London, Eastern Cape, South Africa 🇿🇦

Western Bluebird (Sialia mexicana) is a native, migratory songbird in the Thrushes (Turdidae) family that is 18cm (7 inches) long. Adult male tail, upper parts and throat are deep blue. Breast sides and flanks are chestnut colored, and belly and undertail coverts are gray. Female is duller, brownish gray above, breast and flanks tinged with chestnut, throat is pale gray. It nests in holes in trees and also in nest boxes. Bluebirds are year round residents in local (Monterey County) oak woodlands. Several nesting boxes can be seen in Toro County Park (Monterey County, CA). Diet is mostly insects and berries. It often forages by perching fairly low and flying down to the ground to capture insects, sometimes hovering briefly before pouncing. It may catch insects in mid-air or in foliage.

Breeding: "The western bluebird nests in cavities or in nest boxes, competing with tree swallows, house sparrows, and European starlings for natural nesting locations. Because of the high level of competition, house sparrows often attack western bluebirds for their nests. The attacks are made both in groups or alone. Attacks by starlings can be reduced if the nesting box opening is kept to 1.5 in (38 mm) diameter to avoid takeover. Nest boxes come into effect when the species is limited and dying out due to the following predators: cats, raccoons, opossums, and select birds of prey such as the Cooper's Hawk. Ants, bees, earwigs, and wasps can crawl into the nesting boxes and damage the newborns. Western bluebirds are among the birds that nest in cavities, or holes in trees, or nest boxes. Their beaks are too weak and small to dig out their own holes, so they rely on woodpeckers to make their nest sites for them."

column43:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/16RA8BDi5Y/ 

Images part B of a 2 part observation - Part A here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286744979

The honey-choc Lady Beetles, AKA "Somethingeus deliciosus", apparently already has a name! 😄

A few months ago, in January, we came across some rather unusual hairy little honey-choc-coloured Lady Beetles. They were pupating on a Bugweed plant: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286740919.

We subsequently returned to see them again on the following day once their autumny colours had settled: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286741646. 

A few days later we found another one on our Lemon 🍋 tree: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286742671, and subsequently also on a Society Garlic Chive: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286743766.

In the absence of an identity or name, at that stage, and inspired by the chocolatey grin on the backs of these little beetles, Jan Botha suggested "Somethingeus deliciosus" 😄🧡🤎

Since then, we've been seeing these beetles all over the place, until last week, when we came across this astonishing sight! 😮 Apparently the Somethingeous deliciosus beetles had found something even more delicious!

After one of our bush walks we happened to stroll past one of the many Yellow Bells plants in our area and we noticed that the honey-choc beetles, their eggs, larvae and pupae were all over the plant! What a surprise! 👀 We also found a pupa on a neighbouring Lantana leaf, but we are yet to establish if this is related to feeding, or purely a proximity-related coincidence...

Since we realised that Yellow Bells is categorised as invasive, we did a bit of research...

We came across this interesting fact sheet compiled by Lin Besaans for the Agricultural Research Council, "Mada Polluta, A Lady Beetle Released for Biocontrol of Yellow Bells": https://www.arc.agric.za/arc-ppri/Fact%20Sheets%20Library/Mada%20polluta%20on%20tecoma.pdf.

"The lady beetle Mada polluta Mulsant 1850 (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) was collected on yellow bells (Tecoma stans) in 2007 in Mexico, where the plant is native, and imported into quarantine in South Africa for screening as a potential biocontrol agent. Following several years of testing, the lady beetle was found to be host specific on yellow bells. Permission was obtained for its release, and the first insects were released at various sites in KwaZulu-Natal, Mpumalanga, Gauteng, and North West in the summer of 2013/2014. Releases are on-going, and the distribution map will be updated once establishment has been determined.

Adult beetles are yellow and black, and are about 5 mm long and 4.34 mm wide. Larvae are yellow, with long, branched spines on the dorsal and lateral surfaces. From first instar to fourth instar, larval body length ranges between 2.51 mm and 5.3 mm. Pupae are yellow and brown, and are covered by the old hard, spiny skin of the larva.

Adult females lay clusters of 3-59 eggs on the underside of leaves. The larvae hatch within 7-10 days and feed on the leaves immediately. Larvae go through 4 larval instars (growth stages) before pupating, and emerge as adults within about 36 days. Adults live for up to 4 months, and females reproduce several times during that period.

Both adults and larvae feed on the leaves and, to a lesser extent, on the stems of yellow bells. They consume the leaf area in narrow, short band sets from left to right, then start again below the first set, but without ever consuming the thin line of leaf area that separates the two adjacent sets. In this manner, they skeletonise the leaf.

The lady beetle is expected to contribute significantly to the biological control of yellow bells in South Africa, owing to several factors. Firstly, both adults and larvae are extremely damaging to the plant. Laboratory studies demonstrated that the insects decrease leaf density significantly, stunting the plant’s growth and reducing its competitive ability. Secondly, adult females reproduce rapidly, thus, beetle populations and their associated damage should increase in the field accordingly. Thirdly, this group of beetles (coccinellids) protect themselves chemically from predators and parasitoids, which enhances their chance of survival and, ultimately, their effect on the target weed. Biological control is the only sustainable solution for yellow bells infestations, and it is hoped that the lady beetle will reduce these plants throughout the country, thereby encouraging the indigenous vegetation to recover."

There's another, more recent article by Marleni Arnoldi in Creamer Media's Engineering News, 19 November 2024: "ARC to release invasive-plant controlling beetles in Umkhomazi": https://m.engineeringnews.co.za/article/arc-to-release-invasive-plant-controlling-beetles-in-umkhomazi-2024-11-19, in which it is reported that:

 "The Agricultural Research Council’s (ARC’s) plant health and protection unit will, on November 25, release a leaf-feeding lady beetle called Mada Polluta in Umkhomazi, KwaZulu-Natal, to act as a biological control agent against invasive yellow bells...The release of the beetle, which is a collaboration project between the Department of Forestry, Fisheries and the Environment, the eThekwini municipality and Ezemvelo KwaZulu-Natal Wildlife, was approved for release in 2013, and efforts are now focused on mass rearing and releasing the beetle to help control yellow bell invasions.

In particular, the release of the beetle in Umkhomazi aims to limit the growth and spread of yellow bells in the region. More releases will occur at selected sites across the province that provide suitable habitat for the beetle."

It would appear the preliminary suggestion to introduce this beetle was based on research conducted in this paper by Lulama Gracious Madire, Biocontrol Science and Technology Volume 23 (2013) - Issue 8: "Biology and host range of Mada polluta, a potential biological control agent of Tecoma stans in South Africa": https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09583157.2013.809404.

According to another article by the same author, Lulama Gracious Madire, in Plant Protection News (October 2016 - March 2017) Issue No 109, "Lady beetle (Mada polluta) fully established on yellow bells (Tecoma stans) on the South Coast of KwaZulu-Natal": https://invasives.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/PPRI-News-109.pdf

"Since the release of this beetle, a number of factors have delayed its establishment, including the destruction of most of the release sites through deliberate felling and burning by landowners after initial establishment. Although the beetles recovered at a few felled sites,
none of the beetles were recovered on burned sites. The destruction of the release sites has not only delayed establishment of the beetle, but has also delayed the commencement of its post-release evaluation."

Well it would appear that this beetle has certainly made its way all the way to Gulu! We've since been finding them on Yellow Bells plants all over the place! 😄

From iNat we see Mada sp. Lady Beetles are Plant-Eating Lady Beetles: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/640755-Mada and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?preferred_place_id=6986&taxon_id=640755&view=species, but there 
are no observations as yet of Mada polluta on iNat despite the name apparently being listed: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/673993-Mada-polluta and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=673993&view=species. 

Update: Thanks to Tony Rebelo Mada polluta is now listed on iNat as the Yellow Bells Ladybeetle. Thanks Tony! 🙂 Thanks also to Jaroslav Větrovec* for confirming the ID 🙂

*Jaroslav Větrovec is "a Coccinellidae specialist" 

We managed to contact Lulu to send her regards from the local beetles and she kindly added that: "Indeed, Mada polluta is well established around East London. I visited East London in March, and it is causing significant damage to the Tecoma stans population. This species is specific to yellow bells; it may be found resting on the leaves of other plants when they are defoliated, but it does not feed on or develop on other plants. It is well established at South coast, KZN and Mpumalanga provinces as well." Thanks for that Lulu! 🙂

Reading up a bit further about Yellow Bells or Tecoma Stans: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/48363-Tecoma-stans and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/48363-Tecoma-stans/browse_photos, we found the following:

"Tecoma stans is a species of flowering perennial shrub in the trumpet vine family, Bignoniaceae, that is native to the Americas. Common names include yellow trumpetbush, yellow bells, yellow elder, ginger Thomas. Tecoma stans is the official flower of the United States Virgin Islands and the floral emblem of The Bahamas.

Tecoma stans is a semi-evergreen shrub or small tree, growing up to 10 m tall. It features opposite odd-pinnate green leaves, with 3 to 13 serrate, 8- to 10-cm-long leaflets. The leaflets, glabrous on both sides, have a lanceolate blade 2–10 cm long and 1–4 cm wide, with a long acuminate apex and a wedge-shaped base.

The large, showy, golden yellow, trumpet-shaped flowers are in clusters at the ends of branches. The corolla of the flower is bell- to funnel-shaped, five-lobed (weakly two-lipped), often reddish-veined in the throat and is 3.5 to 8.5 cm long. Flowering takes place from spring to fall, but more profusely from spring to summer.

The fruits, narrow capsules, arise from two carpels and are up to 25 cm long. A fruit contains many yellow seeds with membranopus wings; when the fruit opens upon ripening, these seed are spread by the wind (anemochory). The flowers attract bees, butterflies, and hummingbirds. Apart from sexually by seed, Tecoma stans can also be reproduced asexually by stem cuttings. 

Tecoma stans is native to the Americas. It extends from the southern United States through Mexico, Central America, and the Antilles to northern Venezuela, and through the Andes mountain range to northern Argentina. It was introduced in southern Africa, India, and Hawaii. It is evergreen in moist and warmer regions, but is deciduous in more temperate regions that have a pronounced dry season.

Yellow trumpetbush is a ruderal species, readily colonizing disturbed, rocky, sandy, and cleared land and occasionally becoming an invasive weed. It thrives in a wide variety of ecosystems, from high altitude temperate forests and tropical deciduous and evergreen forests, to xerophilous scrub and the intertropical littoral. It quickly colonizes disturbed, rocky, sandy, and cleared fields. The species prefers dry and sunny regions of the coast. 

Tecoma stans is drought-tolerant and grows well in warm climates. It is cultivated as an ornamental. They are grown in many parts of the world for their beautiful flowering, to adorn streets and gardens. It can be easily propagated by stem cuttings.

The wood of Tecoma stans is used in rustic architecture like bahareque, for the construction of furniture and canoes, or as firewood or charcoal. It is a medicinal plant used against diabetes and against diseases of the digestive system, among other uses. The plant is desirable fodder when it grows in fields grazed by livestock.

It is a very potent anti-venom against cobra venom, used by Pakistani old medicine. It is proved to be better than antiserum, the paste of this plant's leaves are applied topically on the cobra bite. Its bio-chemicals bind with the cobra venom enzymes thus effectively inhibiting the venom.

Tecoma stans is unique in that although it is nontoxic itself, the honey from its flowers is poisonous nonetheless.

Tecoma stans has invasive potential and occasionally becomes a weed. The species is considered invasive in Africa (especially South Africa), South America, Asia, Australia and the Pacific Islands. It now presents a significant danger for biodiversity. It competes with local species and can form thick, almost monospecific thickets."

Fascinating discoveries in Gulu, on the outskirts of East London, Eastern Cape, South Africa 🇿🇦

column43:
A solo visit. I started late (1150) because I could not motivate myself to get out of bed. The weather at my arrival was sunny and 91 degrees ("feels like" 100), with a light breeze. I surveyed Scrub Island Road for the first time this year, and I found an old logging tram that headed west from the end of the road. I followed the tram until it ended; it was a nice shady walk, and provided me with my first Appalachian Brown of Chassahowitzka. (The tram also furnished my first EVER photograph of a Barred Owl in Hernando County!!! Talk about being long overdue)! There were also many Needle Palms along the tram. I stopped at the Dukes' Skippper spot along 3 Bridge Road (finding little) before I headed to my final spot near the start of North Road. I once again encountered an agitated female "Southestern" American Kestrel, so there must be a nest in the kestrel box. I left at 1501, when the weather was sunny, 94 degrees ("feels like" 104), and breezy.

These are my cell-phone photographs (161 records), all time-stamped and geolocated.

Observed an Indigo snake coiled with a coral snake on the path. The coral snake was alive and the Indigo appeared to be attempting to establish a hold on the coral snakes head.
After a few minutes the Indigo's head emerged from under the coil with the coral snake held by the back of its head.

The Indigo then moved off the path into the brush with the coral snake.

Those more familiar with coral snakes who also observed the interaction remarked on site that the coral would be considered a large specimen.
